<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b5e1713dcd24ae6d03086c20c0b343fd?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>The sooner we get rid of endless growth capitalism the better we will be. We will need to re-evaulate our priorities, change laws, and the like to put quality of life for all classes ahead of corporate profits and economic growth as a national priority. We will need to reduce consumption, reduce shipping distances of goods and food, revive localized culture, and work on making a quality of life that can work with less resources and doesn&#8217;t damage the planet further. We will need to rethink the motion that everyone will commute to a 9-5 job everyday and that we can import all of our goods from China and other countries with third-world labor rates. If we can revive the railroad system, develop alternative fuels, and the like we could provide at least some transport to see distant family members. We will also need to adapt to a more slow paced, leisurely lifestyle. Over time, we will need work to put the farms back in the cities again. The easiest way to begin is to learn to start fixing things as opposed to buying new ones, encourage local gardening and get the markets to accept backyard produced goods, and to ban coast to coast freight trucking (if it has to go that far, use rail or boat). Then, we need to flex work hours and days so that we eliminate the rush hour commute (which is the biggest gas waster). We need to replace GDP with national happiness.</p>
